When it closed its doors, there were claims that the crisis-hit attraction crumbled under pressure to pay its staff wages of more than £100,000 per month - just nine days before Christmas.

Angry parents were told to contact their card providers for refunds with many buying tickets for their entire families.

At the time, Mr Llewelyn-Bowen said he had not given any financial support to the project and was unaware of the backer's identity. 

Mr Povey, one of the liquidators, said: 'The directors of Magical Journeys Limited faced a number of significant challenges and attribute the failure to a combination of poor weather hampering site preparation, the temporary closure of the attraction, leading to negative publicity which had an impact on ticket sales, and higher-than-anticipated costs.

